Part 1: Simulation Exercise

1.1 Show the sample mean and compare it to the theroretical mean of the distribution

lambda<- 0.2
n<- 40
set.seed(123)
sim<- matrix(rexp(n*1000,lambda), nrow=1000,ncol=40)
meansim<- apply(sim, 1, mean)
hist(meansim, breaks=40, 
        main = "Comparison of Means (Sample VS Theoretical)", xlab = "Mean Value", ylab = "Frequency of Means")
abline(v = mean(meansim), lty=1, lwd=3, col= "red")
abline(v= 1/lambda, lty = 1, lwd=3, col= "blue")
legend("topright", lty=1, lwd=3, col=c("red", "blue"), legend = c("Sample Mean", "Theoretical Mean"))

#### 1.2 Show how varible the sample is (via variance) and compare it to the theoretical variance of the ditribution

lambda<- 0.2
n<- 40
set.seed(123)
sim<- matrix(rexp(n*1000,lambda), nrow=1000,ncol=40)
varsim<- apply(sim, 1, var)
hist(varsim, breaks = 40,
        main = "Comparison on Variance Among Simulated Samples", xlab="Varience", ylab="Frequency of Variance")
abline(v = mean(varsim), lty=1, lwd=3, col= "red")
abline(v= (1/lambda)^2, lty = 1, lwd=3, col= "blue")
legend("topright", lty=1, lwd=3, col=c("red", "blue"), legend = c("Mean of Sample Variance", "Theoretical Variance"))

1.3 Show the distribution is approximately normal

Normal Distribution by curve
lambda<- 0.2
n<- 40
set.seed(123)
sim<- matrix(rexp(n*1000,lambda), nrow=1000,ncol=40)
meansim<- apply(sim, 1, mean)
hist(meansim, breaks=40, probability = T,
        main = "Distribution of Means", xlab = "Mean Value", ylab = "Density")
lines(density(meansim), lwd= 3, col="red")

# Normal distribution line creation
x <- seq(min(meansim), max(meansim), length=2*n)
y <- dnorm(x, mean=1/lambda, sd=sqrt(((1/lambda)/sqrt(n))^2))
lines(x,y, pch=22, col="blue", lwd=3, lty=2)
legend("topright", lty=c(1,2), lwd=3, col=c("red", "blue"), legend = c("Sample Normal", "Theoretical Normal"))

##### Normal Distribution by Comparing CI

lambda<- 0.2
n<- 40
set.seed(123)
sim<- matrix(rexp(n*1000,lambda), nrow=1000,ncol=40)
meansim<- apply(sim, 1, mean)
simci<- round(mean(meansim) +c(-1,1)*1.96*sd(meansim)/sqrt(n),3)
tci<- round(1/lambda +c(-1,1)*1.96*lambda/sqrt(n),3)
hist(meansim, breaks=40, probability = T,
        main = "Distribution of Means", xlab = "Mean Value", ylab = "Density")
lines(density(meansim), lwd= 3, col="red")

# Normal distribution line creation
x <- seq(min(meansim), max(meansim), length=2*n)
y <- dnorm(x, mean=1/lambda, sd=sqrt(((1/lambda)/sqrt(n))^2))
lines(x,y, pch=22, col="blue", lwd=3, lty=2)
legend("topright", lty=c(1,2), lwd=3, col=c("red", "blue"), legend = c("Sample Normal", "Theoretical Normal"))
abline(v = simci, lty=1, lwd=3, col="Red")
abline(v=tci, lty=2, lwd=3, col="Blue")

2.2 Provide basic summary of the data

Quick observations from the plots, tells us that the length of tooth does increase as the dosage increases for both supplement.When compared between the mean of two supplement as a whole, their means were found between the CI of each supplement. Also, both supplements starts to converge with little difference at 2.0 dose and might suggest that there is no difference between each supplement at high dosage. More statistical analysis are required to define if theres a significant difference between the supplements and at which dosage is the effective ones.

2.3 Use confidence interval and/or hypothesis test to compare tooth growth by supp and dose. (only use the techniques from class, even if theres otehr approaches worth considering)

Assumptions: (1) Data is normal Null Hypothesis by overall: (1) There is no difference between both supplements by means of all dosage Null Hypothesis by Supplement (2) There is no difference between dosage comparing just dosage,(3) There is no difference between supplements at 0.5 dosage of each supplement, (4) There is no difference between both supplements at 1.0 dosage of each supplement, (5) There is no difference between supplements at 2.0 dosage of each supplement. Null Hypothesis by Dosage of each Supplement (6) There is no difference between 0.5 and 1.0 dosage for OJ (7) There is no difference between 1.0 and 2.0 dosage for OJ (8) There is no difference between 0.5 and 2.0 dosage for OJ (9) There is no difference between 0.5 and 1.0 dosage for VC (10) There is no difference between 1.0 and 2.0 dosage for VC (11) There is no difference between 0.5 and 2.0 dosage for VC

Based on Supplement

t.test(len~supp, data=ToothGrowth)

By setting the alpha level to be 0.05%, the two sample t-test (p=0.6063) showed no significant difference when samples were compared between supplements. Null hypothesis (1) cannot be rejected

By comparing the supplements at each dosage level, it was observed that supplements at 0.5 and 1.0 seems to have significant difference between each other. However, as observed in the exploratory plot at 2.0 dosage does not have significant differences observed with means within the range of each others confidence intervals. Hence, we are able to reject null hypothesis for 3,4 but we are not able to reject 5.
